- "Release year" is derived from the release date;
- "Market rank" is the ranking of each browser version within its creator group based on market share.

- A browser is a software application used to access the internet and view web pages;
- The market share of a browser indicates its popularity relative to other browsers;
- The initial release date refers to the date when the browser was first made available;
- The number of versions reflects the development and updates of the browser over time;
- Download counts indicate the popularity and usage of specific browser versions.

- 'Top browsers' refers to the browsers with the highest market share;
- 'Latest release date' is the most recent release date of the browser version;
- 'Current market share' is the market share of the latest version of the browser.

- "latest version" refers to the version with the most recent release date within each browser;
- "release date" is the date when the version was made available;
- "download count" is the number of times the version has been downloaded by users.

- 'Recently updated' refers to browsers that have been updated after January 1, 2023;
- 'Turn of the millennium' refers to the year 2000;
- 'Companies with "Company" in their name' refers to creators whose names include the word 'Company'.

- "Browsers" can be metaphorically thought of as books in a library;
- "Tags" can be thought of as labels or categories assigned to books;
- "Latest version details" include the version number, release date, download count, bug fixes, and new features;
- "Details of the browser" include the browser name, market share, user rating, and last updated date.

- "market share greater than 5%" refers to browsers that have a significant presence in the market;
- "user rating above 4.0" indicates high user satisfaction;
- "recent version released between January 2022 and January 2023" refers to the latest versions of the browsers released within this time frame;
- "accessed more than 100 times" suggests that these browsers are frequently used.

sql:
SELECT creator_name
FROM creators
WHERE creator_name LIKE '%Google%';
